reviewText: Generally speaking, most men are attracted to the subjects of extremes.  Extreme speed, explosions, house demolitions, building demolitions, motorcycle racing, all contact sports . . . and building BIG THINGS (really big things).  This series deals with the design and engineering involved in monumental construction projects.  Every episode involves the transportation and assembly of giant things (skyscrapers, bridges, tunnels), projects that include the use of Big cranes and earth-movers and barges and helicopters.  Definitely, man stuff.  So, take charge of the TV. Reprogram your remote to skip the Hallmark Channel and get a season ticket to Extreme Engineering.

reviewText: It is interesting seeing the challenges encountered in tackling engineering projects.  It is easy for someone who has not been involved in overcoming such engineering challenges to criticize and point the finger of blame! It is easy to criticize Boeing had battery issues or Toyoda for accelerator pedal issues or BP for a deep water drilling accident but it is necessary to learn from issues and continue to make progress.

reviewText: This series are educational & sometimes interesting to watch but what I disliked the most is the way most of the things are dramatically overemphasized and repeated several times during the show. Sometimes the narration of certain stuff are presented as if it is sort of 'catastrophe' waiting to happen. Some of the contents of the series are just speculation and still on drawing board nothing really completed yet but mere plansHaving said, there are several episodes that are very good. I liked the way they show every aspect of engineering including how people must live their lives in order to complete the work. Too bad these series are no longer Prime eligible but I got lucky and crammed all seasons under a week to view it. Amazon must bring them back to Prime members.
